The optical characteristics of the R-NCDs were assessed using three-dimensional fluorescence spectroscopy. As showed in Fig. 4 A, the excitation range was from 500 to 580 nm, accompanied by an emission range from 570 to 690 nm. Interestingly, the R-NCDs displays peak fluorescence at 630 nm when excited at 540 nm, the typical excitation and emission wavelengths of the R-NCDs. Excitingly, the UV–vis spectrum of the R-NCDs in Fig. 4B contains two strong absorption bands at 200–450 nm. The 200 −350 nm band originates from the π−π* transition corresponds to the sp2 domain of CC and CN, and the defect state of n − π* contains the oxygen-containing functional groups about the C−O and CO groups (Zhang et al., 2017). In addition, the emission band of 280 −350 nm corresponds to the π−π* transition about the conjugated CC unit in the carbon core, while the 450-nm emission band correlates with the n − π* transition of the carboxyl functional bond on these R-NCDs surfaces (Fang et al., 2017; Singhal et al., 2017; Xu et al., 2024; Yoo et al., 2021). Therefore, the R-NCDs exhibited excellent water-solubility across a wide wavelength range. The impact of time and fluorescence intensity on the stability of the R-NCDs was investigated at room temperature (25 ± 10 °C). As demonstrated in Fig. 4 C, the fluorescence intensity of the R-NCDs remains essentially unchanged over 36 h, accompanied by a relative standard deviation (RSD) of 1.9 %, indicating that the R-NCDs exhibit exceptional stability, which is advantageous for practical applications. Additionally, the fluorescence lifetime of the R-NCDs in Fig. 4D was determined using time-correlated single-photon counting, and the decay trajectory was fitted with Eq. (1):
